         <div type="translation">
            <p>Θεοτόκε βοήθει Θεοδώρῳ.</p>
            <p xml:lang="en">Mother of God, help Theodoros.</p>
            <p xml:lang="de">Muttergottes, hilf Theodoros.</p>
            <p xml:lang="el">Θεοτόκε βοήθησε το Θεόδωρο.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" subtype="text">
            <p xml:lang="en">The upper part of the seal is damaged, so we do not know for sure
                    whether the monogram on the reverse is fully preserved. If we assume that the
                    monogram is fully preserved, then it would correspond to the monogram type Zacos
                    186, with the omicron inscribed in the rho and the name in the dative case.
                    Alternatively, it can be assumed that there is a letter above the pi, either an
                    upsilon (see the monogram type Zacos 179), in which case the name would be in
                    the genitive, or an omicron (see the monogram type Zacos 185). There seems to be
                    no place for an OV ligature. No parallels of this seal are known, but there are
                    many specimens showing on the obverse the same invocative monogram (Laurent,
                    type I) and on the reverse a similar cruciform monogram, with the name Theodoros
                    in the genitive (with an OV ligature) or, more rarely, in the dative (with an
                    omicron drown at the top of the rho).[1] Quite often there is no decoration in
                    the quarters of the name monogram, except for one seal published in the
                            <bibl>
                  <ptr target="DOsealsOnline"/>, which shows four stars (<citedRange unit="entry">
                     <ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1947.2.1720">BZS.1947.2.1720</ref>
                  </citedRange>)</bibl>.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" subtype="footnotes">
                <!--add "Zografopoulos2005" to bibliography: Zografopoulos K. J., Die byzantinischen Bleisiegel aus Karthago [PhD Diss.], Wien 2005.-->
            <p xml:id="footnote-1">[1] In the genitive: (1) Tatis Collection, no. 2315,
                    published in <bibl>
                  <ptr target="CheynetTatış"/>, no. <citedRange unit="entry">8.58</citedRange>
               </bibl>; (2) DO <ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1958.106.5006/view">BZS.1958.106.5006</ref> (Zacos Collection), published in <bibl>
                  <ptr target="Zacos1"/>, no. <citedRange unit="entry">1619</citedRange>
               </bibl>
                    and in <bibl>
                  <ptr target="DOsealsOnline"/>
               </bibl>; (3) DO <ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1947.2.1720/view">BZS.1947.2.1720</ref> and (4) DO <ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1958.106.4997/view">BZS.1958.106.4997</ref>, both published in <bibl>
                  <ptr target="DOsealsOnline"/>
               </bibl>. In the dative, with an omicron drown at
                    the top of the rho: DO <ref target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1958.106.2340/view">BZS.1958.106.2340</ref>, published in <bibl>
                  <ptr target="Zacos1"/>, no.
                            <citedRange unit="entry">1621</citedRange>
               </bibl> and in <bibl>
                  <ptr target="DOsealsOnline"/>
               </bibl>. On a seal published by Zografopoulos
                    the case is unclear, as the upper part of the monogram is missing (Karthago, no.
                    18/6/1, published in <bibl>
                  <ptr target="Zografopoulos2005"/>, no. <citedRange unit="entry">Θ 12</citedRange>
               </bibl>).</p>
         </div>
